For {= aircraft_model =}+ aircraft, engine, or helicopter models with FAA jurisdiction, find at least {= ad_number =} FAA Airworthiness Directives in canonical `YYYY-WW-DD` form effective in {= target_year =} per model, name each manufacturer Service Bulletin the AD cites as compliance documentation in the manufacturer's own identifier convention (at least {= manufacturer_sb =} per AD), and supply a source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL) whose page content substantiates the chain — naming the AD identifier, the affected model, the effective date, the unsafe condition, and showing that the AD adopts the named SB.

Each URL must explicitly identify both the AD and the SB it cites with the citation direction AD → SB clear — not aggregator landing pages without per-AD detail, search-engine result snippets, press-wire republications that don't name the SB, or standalone manufacturer SB documents without the AD context.

Requirements:
- The page must support the AD becoming effective in {= target_year =} — not a different year and not still in proposal stage.
- The page must name the claimed model as falling within the AD's applicability — model variants and family designations are fine when the AD's text covers them.
- The page must describe the unsafe condition the AD addresses (broken parts, fatigue cracks, malfunctioning systems, manufacturing defects, etc.) — not just the existence of an inspection requirement.
- The page must substantiate that AD `ad_number` adopts the named Service Bulletin — citation direction is AD → SB (the AD names the SB), not SB → AD.
